I am using MonoGame 3.0 Stable, and I created a new project with the VS 2012 Template 'MonoGame Windows Phone 8 Project'. 

All that I have done to the template is edit 'Game1.cs', and add this code to my `Update()` method:

```
protected override void Update(GameTime gameTime)
{
    // TODO: Add your update logic here
    base.Update(gameTime);

    if (TouchPanel.GetCapabilities().IsConnected)
    {
        foreach (TouchLocation touch in TouchPanel.GetState())
        {
            Debug.WriteLineIf(
                touch.State != TouchLocationState.Moved, 
                String.Format("Touch {0}\n\t" +
                                "State: {1}\n\t" +
                                "Position: {2}\n\t" +
                                "Pressure: {3}\n", 
                                touch.Id, touch.State, touch.Position, touch.Pressure
                )
            );
        }
    }
}
```

Now, when I run this on my Nokia Lumia 920, I get the following output:

<pre>
Touch 2
    State: Pressed
    Position: {X:Infinity Y:Infinity}
    Pressure: 0

Touch 2
    State: Released
    Position: {X:Infinity Y:Infinity}
    Pressure: 0

Touch 3
    State: Pressed
    Position: {X:Infinity Y:Infinity}
    Pressure: 0

Touch 3
    State: Released
    Position: {X:Infinity Y:Infinity}
    Pressure: 0

Touch 4
    State: Pressed
    Position: {X:Infinity Y:Infinity}
    Pressure: 0

Touch 4
    State: Released
    Position: {X:Infinity Y:Infinity}
    Pressure: 0
</pre>


No matter what I do, the touch's location is always infinity. After looking in the debugger a bit, it appears that the `_touchScale` variable is `{X:Infinity Y:Infinity}`, which seems to me like it may be a problem.

After digging in the source for `TouchPanel`, it appears that the problem is here:

```
_touchScale = new Vector2(  (float)DisplayWidth / windowSize.X,
                            (float)DisplayHeight / windowSize.Y);
```

For some reason, on my windows phone, it appears that it isn't able to get a value for windowSize (or windowSize is set to 0, resulting in the infinity), which probably means a bug exists in `WPGameWindow`.

I'll be trying to step through the source after I post this to figure out exactly what's going on, but I wanted to report this here in case there's a known solution to this problem.

