Texture2D.GetData is using d3dContext.MapSubresource to load a staging texture that can be read by the CPU.

It only uses the "out" stream and then reads the requested number of elements out of that stream into the data buffer.

This seems to work great on my laptop and my Surface, but I tried running one of my games on my PC with an ATI Radeon of some sort (from 2011) and my graphics look messed up.  I traced it back to differences in the Texture2D.GetData which I subsequently use to draw some pixelated sprites.

So debugging side by side with my laptop and desktop at the point of calling GetData on the same texture, my laptop returns one set of Colors and my desktop returns another set of Colors.

Digging in further, I noticed that the actual data stream coming from MapSubresource was different.

I added some code to capture the return variable (MapSubresource actually returns a DataBox) and inspected the DataBox on both machines.  On my Laptop the RowPitch was 128 which lines up with the expectation that 4 x 32 (RGBA is 4 bytes, 32 pixels is the width of my texture) is the RowPitch.

However, there's no guaranteeing that the mapped resource will be perfectly packed.  My Desktop has a RowPitch of 256, so there's a lot of data that needs to be skipped over.

In other words, just blindly using:

``` C#
stream.ReadRange(data, startIndex, elementCount);
```

Will not account for RowPitch and will yield incorrect Color data on some machines.

I have a work around in place (that proved to me this was the issue) which changes the last part of GetData to look like this:

``` C#
int mipSize = 0;
                    var box = d3dContext.MapSubresource(stagingTex, 0, 0, SharpDX.Direct3D11.MapMode.Read, SharpDX.Direct3D11.MapFlags.None, out mipSize);

                    var dataPtr = box.DataPointer;
                    var start = startIndex;
                    for (int i = 0; i < height; i++)
                    {
                        SharpDX.Utilities.Read(dataPtr, data, start, width);
                        dataPtr += box.RowPitch;
                        start += width;
                    }
```

This allows the GetData to yield correct results on both of my machines.

However, the above code is not something I would propose as a pull request because its not accounting for the elementCount parameter (I just happen to always ask for all elements in my usage so this workaround is very specific at the moment). 

Also there are more complexities when considering multiple depths (and then having to factor in DepthPitch which I am ignoring here).

Just wanted to bring this issue up in case someone with more graphics experience wants to make a solid/generic fix and in case anyone else runs into this they can now know the reason why.
